# Solidity Style and Safety

## Errors

Prefer `if (condition) revert CustomError(args)`. This ensures compatibility across chains that may not support opcodes required by newer compiler versions. `require(condition, CustomError())` (available in `^0.8.27` or via IR in `^0.8.26`) is acceptable only when the file's pragma already targets that version: do not bump pragma just to use it.

Avoid bumping pragma versions without verifying that any newly introduced opcodes are supported on all major chains. Check before introducing any version that uses new opcodes (e.g. `0.8.24` introduced `mcopy`).

Error naming follows [ERC-6093](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-6093) rationale:
- Domain prefix: `ERC<number>` if violating an ERC spec; otherwise the component name (`Governor`, `ECDSA`, `Timelock`).
- Include the offending value(s) as arguments for debuggability.
- Never declare the same error name twice across the library: duplicate names cause identifier conflicts when inheriting from multiple contracts.

Error location priority: existing ERC definition > interface/library > implementation > extension.

## Events

Emit **after** state changes. `PastTense` verb names (`OwnershipTransferred`). ERC-standard events use the tense specified in the ERC. Define in the interface or at the top of the emitting contract.

## NatSpec

`@dev` is the only tag rendered by the OZ documentation engine. Do not use `@notice` in implementation contracts: it does not appear in generated docs. `@notice`, `@param`, `@return` appear in interface files where ERC specs are kept as-is.

- Single-line: `/// @dev Description.`
- Multi-line: `/** @dev Description. */`
- Document everything: public, internal, private functions; events; errors; constructors.
- Pure relay overrides: `/// @inheritdoc InterfaceName`
- Overrides with added requirements: `/** @dev See {Interface-functionName}. \n\n Requirements: ... */`
- Cross-references: `{ContractName-functionName}` syntax
- Prose section headers: `Requirements:`, `NOTE:`, `WARNING:`, `IMPORTANT:`

## Imports

100% named curly-brace imports. Relative paths within `contracts/`. No wildcards:
```solidity
import {IERC20, IERC20Metadata} from "../../interfaces/IERC20.sol";
```

## File structure order

SPDX + provenance comment, pragma, imports, contract NatSpec, contract declaration. Inside the body: `using`, structs/enums, state vars, constants, errors, events, constructor, modifiers, external/public functions, internal functions, private functions.

## Pragma

- Interfaces: `pragma solidity >=0.X.Y;` (permissive for composability)
- Implementations and libraries: `pragma solidity ^0.8.XX;`

## ERC-7201 storage

ERC-7201 is NOT a general pattern. Upgradeable variants are auto-generated by the transpiler. Use ERC-7201 only when namespacing is genuinely necessary (e.g. `Initializable.sol`) and document why in NatSpec. When used, required elements: `@custom:storage-location` on the struct, inline formula comment above the constant, `$` as the storage pointer variable name, `// solhint-disable-next-line var-name-mixedcase` before any function using `$`.

## Assembly

Always annotate `assembly ("memory-safe")`. Omitting it disables memory optimizer passes and increases gas costs. Include inline comments for non-trivial operations.

Memory literals: hexadecimal (`mload(0x40)`, `mstore(add(ptr, 0x20), value)`). Bit-shift amounts: decimal (`shl(128, value)`).

## `unchecked`

Only with an inline invariant comment (omittable only when the reason is immediately apparent from the line directly above):
```solidity
unchecked {
    // Overflow not possible: value <= fromBalance <= totalSupply.
    _balances[from] = fromBalance - value;
}
```

## Casting

Narrowing integer casts always use `SafeCast.toUintXX()`. Direct Solidity casts only after an explicit bounds check you can point to.

## Immutables and constants

- `constant`: compile-time known values, `ALL_CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES`
- `immutable`: constructor-set values, `_camelCase`
- Add `/// @custom:oz-upgrades-unsafe-allow state-variable-immutable` only when the value must not change across upgrades for security/correctness reasons (e.g. a trusted forwarder address). Do not add it for values that are acceptable to change in an upgrade.

## Inheritance ordering

The relative order of bases in `is A, B, C` must be globally consistent. CI runs `scripts/checks/inheritance-ordering.js` to detect conflicts. Verify ordering after any change to an `is` list.
